<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>Wm : i3</p> <p>Ds : xorg</p> <p>Xinit</p> <p>Compositor: picom</p> <p>File manager : Nautilus (gnome-files)</p> <p>Additional relevant packages: gvfs , gvfs-mtp ,gvfs-nfs , udisk2, polkit , polkit-gnome , ntfs-3g</p> <p>Fstab :</p> <p>/dev/sd1 mounted to /mnt/boot/efi</p> <p>/dev/sd2 swap (resume enabled)</p> <p>/dev/sd3 mounted to /mnt</p> <p>/dev/sd4 mounted to /mnt/home</p> <p>/dev/sd5 is the ntfs partition mounted to none.</p> <p>Now , if one install gnome group , the Nautilus can automatically mount the ntfs partition virtually with the help of ntfs-3g polkit and udisk2.</p> <p>Expecting to do the same with i3wm and Nautilus with the above mentioned softwares</p> <p>Need step by step guide to achieve the desired result where double click the ntfs drive automounts it and upon entering the password the drive becomes accessible.</p> <p>For now I&#39;ve permanently mounted it using fstab using the type as ntfs-3g and default. But I&#39;m missing the additional authentication layer of password protection.</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/zeepers_13"> /u/zeepers_13 </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/wj25iw/setup_gvfs_for_mounting_drives/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/wj25iw/setup_gvfs_for_mounting_drives/">[comments]</a></span>